In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims November as National Native American Heritage Month. He acknowledges the significant contributions of Native Americans to the country's culture and emphasizes the importance of honoring their legacy. The President also acknowledges the history of violence, discrimination, and deprivation that Native Americans have endured, but expresses a commitment to working towards a brighter future and strengthening the nation-to-nation partnerships. He highlights the steps his administration has taken to respect tribal sovereignty, settle legal disputes, promote justice for Native Americans, and provide opportunities for success. The President also mentions investments in infrastructure, healthcare, and protection of tribal lands. He calls upon all Americans to commemorate the month with appropriate programs and activities and designates November 28, 2014, as Native American Heritage Day.